# Veterinary E-commerce Weekly Intelligence Brief
### An Automated AI-Powered Industry Intelligence Tool
**Author:** Samantha Bell  
**Built With:** R · Claude AI (Anthropic) · Web Fetch

---

## Goal

To build a fully automated tool that gathers the latest veterinary e-commerce 
industry information — including newly released products, competitor activity, 
recalls, and external market trends — from pre-determined trusted sources. 
Claude AI agents gather, summarize, and format the content into a structured 
weekly brief delivered to stakeholders every Monday morning.

---

## Audience

Primary audience is the e-commerce team, with potential for disseminating 
findings to leadership or other teams as appropriate.

---

## Why It Matters

Staying ahead of industry trends and identifying risks and opportunities in a 
timely manner allows the team to take targeted actions to grow the business and 
better support the communities they serve. This tool replaces hours of manual 
effort spent checking industry publications and writing summaries — delivering 
consistent, grounded, executive-ready intelligence on a reliable weekly cadence.

---

## Role of AI in This Project

This project uses two Claude AI agents working in sequence:

- **Research Agent** — given a list of trusted industry source URLs, the agent 
fetches each one using Claude's web fetch tool and extracts recent, relevant 
findings. It returns structured data including summaries, verbatim quotes, 
publication dates, and cited URLs.

- **Writing Agent** — receives the cleaned research output and synthesizes it 
into a structured VP-level executive brief using Claude's extended thinking 
capability. The brief is strictly grounded in the research data — the agent 
is explicitly instructed not to supplement findings with its own knowledge.

AI saves hours of employee time that would otherwise be spent manually checking 
web articles and writing summaries. Tight control prompts in agent setup, 
combined with a strong R code foundation, ensure consistent and auditable 
results week over week.

---

## How It Works

The workflow runs automatically every Monday morning via Windows Task Scheduler 
and is triggered by knitting a single R Markdown file. Power Automate detects 
the finished PDF in the output folder and distributes it to stakeholders.
industry_sources (URLs)
│
▼
┌───────────────────┐
│  Freshness Check  │  Filters sources to those with content
│                   │  published within the lookback window
└───────────────────┘
│
▼
┌───────────────────┐
│  Research Agent   │  Claude + web_fetch fetches each source
│                   │  Returns structured JSON findings
└───────────────────┘
│
▼
┌───────────────────┐
│  Quality Filter   │  Removes rows missing dates or citations
└───────────────────┘
│
▼
┌───────────────────┐
│  Writing Agent    │  Claude synthesizes findings into
│                   │  a structured executive brief
└───────────────────┘
│
▼
┌───────────────────┐
│  PDF Renderer     │  briefing_to_pdf.R renders the brief
│                   │  into a branded PDF
└───────────────────┘
│
▼
Stakeholder Distribution (Power Automate)
---

## Output

The tool produces three files on each run, saved to the configured output 
directory:

| File | Description |
|---|---|
| `YYYY-MM-DD Research Agent Results.xlsx` | Raw structured findings from the Research Agent |
| `YYYY-MM-DD Writing Agent Results.xlsx` | Raw brief text returned by the Writing Agent |
| `YYYY-MM-DD Home Delivery Industry Briefing.pdf` | Branded PDF brief distributed to stakeholders |

A weekly token log (`research_agent_log_YYYY_WXX.csv`) is also maintained for 
cost monitoring and auditing.

